cs.CL, cs.AI, cs.IR, cs.LG, cs.CY 

This paper focuses on using machine learning algorithms to quantify human curiosity in the digital world, specifically in the context of clickbait headlines. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CL (Computation and Language), which deals with natural language processing and machine learning for language-related tasks. 

The paper also draws on theories from humanities and social sciences, indicating a potential fit with cs.CY (Computers and Society) or cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). 

The use of unsupervised and supervised machine learning algorithms suggests a potential fit with cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.LG (Machine Learning), while the focus on measuring the strength of the stimulus to generate reader curiosity suggests a potential fit with cs.IR (Information Retrieval).
